Written evidence submitted by[bold] [bold]Scottish Environment LINK[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Land, sea and air[bold]Land, sea and air are the spaces where life exists on our planet. They are the fundamental spheres of our environment and together constitute the biosphere.  As a species, we share these spaces with the other species and the natural, physical universe. In 
[normal]this shared space, whether urban, rural or wild, we depend upon the other species, as they depend upon us. The principles we offer for the land in this submission (and the suggestions as to how they might be applied) underlie our approach to the land, but 
[normal]to the seas and the air also. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]LINK welcomes the opportunity to contribute to 
[normal]the House of Commons’ 
[normal]Sco
[normal]ttish Affairs Committee
[normal] consultation on comprehensive land reform in Scotland
[normal].
[normal] We have only a limited mandate to offer comments on the economic and social aspects of land reform
[normal],
[normal] but 
[normal]we 
[normal]hope that we might offer a significant perspective with regard to 
[normal]many
[normal] of these concerns and, in particular, to 
[normal]environmental concerns.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In this sub
[normal]mission we seek to 
[normal]outline our broad views on
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We then
[normal] 
[normal]summarise our aspirations for public policy governing the relationship between the
[normal] land and the people of Scotland.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What constitutes Land Reform?[bold]Much of the debate on land reform has been about land ownership, almost always acknowledging that ownership affects land use,
[normal] but paying 
[normal]so
[normal] little attention to 
[normal]the way we use land as to 
[normal]amount to ignoring the issue. 
[normal]It is land use
[normal] 
[normal]which most concerns LINK and its members. We are aware that a new type of owner 
[normal]might[bold] change the use they make of 
[normal]a piece of
[normal] land, but we are also aware that the new owner might stick, to all intents and purpose
[normal]s
[normal], to exactly the same usage.
[normal] From an ecological perspective it is NOT the ownership of the land that is important, but the way the land is used.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In LINK we start from the position that much of the way we use the land of Scotland currently is not sustaina
[normal]ble. Huge economic, social and environmental benefits could be obtained from improving the levels of sustainability in the way we use the land – but if land reform does not lead to a major change in 
[normal]attitudes to 
[normal]land use it might be a missed opportunity, a
[normal]nd, at worst 
[normal]positively harmful to our environment
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]W
[normal]hile as LINK we are 
[normal]primarily 
[normal]interested in the use of the land rather than necessarily who owns it (since you can have good and bad examples of all kinds of ownership), we 
[normal]readily
[normal] acknowledge that the way
[normal] most of
[normal] the land is currently used is being driven by the 
[normal]historic patterns of usage and by 
[normal]subsidy
[normal] 
[normal]systems.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The
[normal]se
[normal] historically established patterns of 
[normal]ownership 
[normal]and our 
[normal]public institutions
[normal] and policies
[normal] 
[normal]have led to 
[normal]most
[normal] of the problems 
[normal]and 
[normal]prompting the 
[normal]solutions 
[normal]we have identified in the 
[normal]section on 
[normal]‘
[normal]our aspirations
[normal]’
[normal] at the end of this submission. We call for much needed 
[normal]legal protections for the ecosystems, public accountability of landowners, equitable taxation and bal
[normal]an
[normal]ced subsidy regimes, because so much current ownership is for single or limited land uses, with little or no reference to
[normal] the public interest
[normal] and the principles of sustainability. 
[normal]It is time for the [bold]land[bold] debate to [bold]give [bold]equal space[bold] to land [bold]ownership and [bold]to [bold]land [bold]use.[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Defining Communities[bold]LINK believes that t
[normal]he health of our democracy relies on recognition of the existence of communities of both place, and interest, and the representative function of people who have the assent of both types of community.
[normal] We hope that the concept of “community ownership” is 
[normal]interpreted
[normal] by the 
[normal]Committee 
[normal]to the ownership of land by communities in both senses. We ask 
[normal]that it be
[normal] note
[normal]d
[normal] that some LINK members own significant areas of land in Scotland and that we consider this to
[normal] be land held in trust for the communities of citizens who are our members – and for the community that is the nation. A fuller explanation of our views on the definition of community can be found in our MSP and Councillors briefing:
[normal]http://www.scotlink.org/files/policy/ParliamentaryBriefings/LINKDefiningCommunityEpwrmt.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ownership [bold]You can’t “own” a cloud, or 
[normal]the rain
[normal], or a river. Nobody “owns” a 
[normal]wild animal
[normal] under Scots law
[normal]. 
[normal]For these reasons
[normal], you
[normal] can't 
[normal]“
[normal]own
[normal]”
[normal] the land, the sea or the air
[normal] in the 
[normal]same way you can exclusively own a piece of moveable property
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Nor can you own land intimately (albeit for a limited period of time) 
[normal]as you can intellectual
[normal] property
[normal]. When land, sea and air
[normal] are “owned”, it is conditional on the understanding that
[normal] they are already, in fact rather than 
[normal]a 
[normal]legal 
[normal]construct
[normal], 
[normal]shared
[normal] 
[normal]jointly
[normal] by all 
[normal]members of all species who use that
[normal] 
[normal]space. This
[normal] 
[normal]joint 
[normal]space is the ecosystem, and for 
[normal]both legal and scientific purposes, we all live in one space. We all live in an ecosystem
[normal] – the biosphere -
[normal] and 
[normal]a small part of 
[normal]this 
[normal]ecosystem can 
[normal]be "owned"
[normal] purely
[normal] 
[normal]with
[normal]in the legal 
[normal]limitations
[normal],
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]with 
[normal]the very
[normal] real inclusion of all others. Legal o
[normal]wnersh
[normal]ip of land is conditional, therefore, 
[normal]on the understanding that such "ownership" is subsidiary to land bei
[normal]ng a part of the common wealth
[normal] of all people and all species
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Several members of LINK “own” land
[normal] (
[normal]as do many other non-Governmental organisations rep
[normal]resenting communities of place and interest
[normal] in urban and rural settings
[normal])
[normal]. Such ownership is an important means to achieving environmental and cultural 
[normal]conservation objectives. T
[normal]he legal rights from such ownership are important 
[normal]in this respect
[normal],
[normal] and should be protected
[normal]. The land concerned is 
[normal]managed in full recognition of the limitations and duties of such “ownership”
[normal],
[normal] including the responsibilities to other people and other species.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Some of the LINK members with Scottish land holdings have unde
[normal]rtaken a joint study of their ownership of land and the results of this project are available at:
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.perth.uhi.ac.uk/s
[normal]pecialistcentres/cms/activities/Documents/Final%20NGO%20Land%20Report%2024%2004%2013.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stewardship and Sustainability[bold]Many environmentalists and conservationists do not readily accept the notion of human dominion over the biosphere held by some relig
[normal]ious or humanist groups, but we all recognise the simple fact of human history and presence. People have an enormous impact on the biosphere and a duty to manage our activities responsibly, particularly where our use of space threatens the very existence o
[normal]f other species. We believe that our history 
[normal]demonstrates the need for an acceptance of the idea that our species has a duty of “stewardship” of the environment, however that might be defined. Since the last ice age human society has used and changed the v
[normal]ast bulk of Scottish land directly – through agriculture, deforestation, reforestation, urbanisation, mineral extraction and other uses. Indirectly, all of the land of Scotland is farther affected by human activity through global processes such as climate 
[normal]change or damage to the ozone layer.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]LINK has no preference between the many types of limited legal ownership or dominion of land by people. All such forms can provide either benign or malign stewardship within the principles of sustainability we believ
[normal]e in. 
[normal]We 
[normal]have, however, set out our wish 
[normal]to see 
[normal]“
[normal]rea
[normal]l subsidiarity, where decisions 
[normal]are taken at the ne
[normal]arest appropriate and practical 
[normal]level, and
[normal] where communities of place and 
[normal]interest can
[normal] assess the long-term economic, 
[normal]social and envir
[normal]onmental consequenc
[normal]es for their 
[normal]lives and the liv
[normal]es of future generations before 
[normal]decisions are made.
[normal]” This view and other details of our broader manifesto can be seen at:
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.
[normal]scotlink.org/files/publication/other/LINKReferendumChallenge2012.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Environmentalists and conservationists do not seek, generally or widely, to “re-establish wilderness” or “reclaim all land from human use”, as has been sometimes claimed - but we do s
[normal]eek to ensure that human land use respects the ecosystem and biodiversity, together with our landscape, cultural and historic legacy, and that the land is sustained for future generations. This aim includes our mainly limited, or sometimes zero, interventi
[normal]on in areas of land we “own” as a community of interest. Scotland has obligations in international law to achieve sustainability – and in this we believe Scotland must follow the precepts and definitions laid out in the 1987 report of the Brundtland Commis
[normal]sion, ‘Our Common Future’.
[normal]&#xa0;
