[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Our Aspirations[bold]Please find here a summary of our aspirations for public policy governing the relationship between the land and the people of Scotland.
[normal] We believe that this area of public policy is in need of reform urgently if we are to achieve truly sustainable development.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We want a Scotland where……[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]…..[bold] all land owners and managers understand and observe defined environmental rights and responsibili[bold]ties.[bold] We recognise and understand that the Scottish community has the right and shall decide upon the system for the economic and social division of the land between people. This division, however constituted, must be balanced by a full understanding of th
[normal]e shared aspects of our dominion over land - the ecosystem cycles and services and the biodiversity that are an inseparable 
[normal]function of the space. L
[normal]egal protections must be put in place to ensure the integrity of these cycles, services and biodiversity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]…..[bold] the ownership or dominion over land is open and transparent.[bold] We need public registers of land that allow us to know exactly who bears the legal duties and responsibilities for ecosystem cycles and services within any de
[normal]fined space – in order that these
[normal] duties and responsibilities
[normal] can be enforced
[normal] and the ecosystem services protected
[normal]. This transparency must cover all land
[normal],
[normal] and ownership 
[normal]and management 
[normal]by communities, ind
[normal]ividuals and corporate entities. It should 
[normal]allow for the identification of ‘absentee’ 
[normal]owners who do not live on the land owned.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]…..[bold] all public policy for land is set out in a democratically established Land Use Strategy.[bold] The strategy should be developed from that established in the Climate Change (Scotland) Act (2009) and should continue to be based upon the principles of environmental, social and economic sustainability. It should ensure that both communities and the eco
[normal]system are sustained for future 
[normal]generations. 
[normal]It should include 
[normal]efficient processes to ensure the accountability of land 
[normal]manag
[normal]ers for their performance in delivering the strategy 
[normal]and refer to
[normal] effective regulatory system
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]We
[normal] set out our view of these princ
[normal]iples in the paper ‘Li
[normal]ving with the Land’ which can be found at:
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.scotlink.org/files/publication/LINKReports/LINKReportLivingwithLand.pdf
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]…..[bold] the [bold]planning and regulatory systems for land use take account of global, national and local [bold]terrestrial, freshwater and marine [bold]ecosystem impacts.[bold] We need protections for ecosystem cycles, services and biodiversity which are based on the best available science 
[normal]- including the clear designation of spaces and appropriate management responsibilities where threatened species are located, in order that biodiversity is maintained.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]……[bold] any land taxation is designed to be economically, socially and environmentally susta[bold]inable.[bold] It should be equitable, and underpinned by an awareness of the effect of the fiscal regime on the ecosystem and biodiversity. Alongside the promotion of economic and social development, one of the core purposes of any land taxation should be the pr
[normal]otection of the ecosystem and biodiversity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]……[bold] any public policy subsidy for land use fully balances[bold] economic, social and [bold]environmental concerns.[bold] Public policy should recognise that unbalanced subsidy regimes can cause severely dangerous impacts to commun
[normal]ities, the ecosystem and biodiversity.
[normal] Such public policy should also be consistent and coherent in all its many strands.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]…..[bold] [bold]openness and public participation are central features of our governance for land use.[bold] 
[normal]We want the methods and processes of government at 
[normal]local and national 
[normal]levels 
[normal]t
[normal]o be open and properly transparent and, as a matter of course, to include genuine representatives of our communities of place and interest in all political decision-making
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]….. [bold]t[bold]here is [bold]recognition[bold] that[bold] the term ‘community’ applies to both communities of place and communities of interest.[bold] We want to see a balance
[normal] 
[normal]between the views of local communities and communities that seek to apply principles relating to national and global is
[normal]sues of concern such as the fight against climate change or the protection of ecosystems and biodiversity.
[normal] We believe that the community interest is best represented when communities of place and interest co-operate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]…[bold].. the traditional right to roam of S[bold]cots [bold]is maintained.[bold] The Land Reform (Scotland) Act (2003) set out in legislation for the first time the right of public access to land in Scotland
[normal], with the attendant responsibilities of the public and land managers
[normal]. We want to see this right jealously gua
[normal]rded and full
[normal] and continuing
[normal] recognition of the underlying principle that land ‘ownership’ is conditional and limited in Scotland – and subject to public rights and interest.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]….. [bold]adequate[bold] procedures for the resolution of conflicts concerning land and environmental protection[bold] are established[bold].[bold] This should include provision for the required legal and scientific expertise in Scotland’s courts and tribunals, and for s
[normal]pecialist courts or tribuna
[normal]ls if
[normal] necessary.
